Social Media Do's and Don'ts for College Students
 DO's

Think before you post — Ask yourself: Would I be comfortable if my professor, parent, or future employer saw this?
Keep your profiles professional — Use a clear profile photo and a bio that reflects your identity positively.
Engage respectfully — Respond to others with courtesy, even when you disagree.
Protect your privacy — Adjust privacy settings and avoid sharing personal details like your location, address, or phone number publicly.
Credit original creators — Always give proper attribution when sharing someone else's work, ideas, or images.
Use social media to network — Connect with professionals, join academic communities, and follow industry leaders in your field.

 DON'Ts

Don't post in anger or haste — Emotional posts made impulsively can damage relationships and reputations permanently.
Don't share misinformation — Always verify information from credible sources before reposting or sharing.
Don't overshare personal information — Avoid posting your daily schedule, location check-ins, or financial details.
Don't engage in cyberbullying — Mocking, harassing, or publicly shaming others online has serious personal and legal consequences.
Don't ignore digital footprints — Everything you post, like, or comment on contributes to your online reputation, which employers and institutions can view.
Don't plagiarise online content — Sharing or repurposing others' work without permission or credit is both unethical and potentially illegal.


